msContents.summary: This volume, written in France circa 1300, mostly consists of the Summa de vitiis of Guilelmus Peraldus, followed by a shorter treatise on the virtues, with pages of notes bound in at the beginning and end. The text is written in Gothic textualis with several changes of hand and occasional manicules in the side margins and stemmata or lists in the lower margin. Its decoration largely consists of red initials, paragraph marks, and rubrics. A dangling catchword at the end of quire 27 (fol. 222v) suggests that at least one gathering at the end of the Summa de vitiis is missing.

msItem.author: Guilelmus Peraldus, approximately 1190-1271

supportDesc.extent: ii+317+ii; 184 x 134 mm bound to 195 x 140 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil, upper right recto; medieval foliation in Roman numerals in top margin, beginning at fol. 5r; one folio (modern 36) not counted in medieval foliation, and two folios, medieval ccxviii and ccxix, are misplaced after medieval ccxxvii (modern 230); references in this record are to modern foliation in pencil

p.signatures: Quires 3-21 signed with roman numerals I-XX, quires 28-33 signed with roman numeral I-V, center lower margin of last verso; many partly trimmed away

p.catchwords: Horizontal catchwords, lower right last verso

layoutDesc.layout: One column of thirty-three to forty-one lines; prickings visible; written area: 156 x 108 mm

decoDesc.decoNote: Capitals, one-line to six-line, mostly two-line and in red, in some brief sections alternating red and blue with contrasting penwork; rubrication and paragraph marks in red

binding.p: Nineteenth-century wooden boards and black morocco, gilt tooled floral borders on sides, gilt back, gilt edges, in cloth case

history.provenance: Purchased in Paris, 1397; Rome (according to illegible sixteenth-century note); at the abbey of Moyenmoutiers, 1717 (shelfmark X.1.46); Davis and Orioli, Cat. 19, June, 1917, no. 5; (directly to?) John Frederick Lewis, Philadelphia; given by his widow, Anne Baker Lewis, to the Free Library of Philadelphia in 1936
